 implications for Holocaust education development for future generations, in Israel and worldwide. Special attention is given to the evolving nature of contemporary multimedia society in which youth are inundated with stimuli of all kinds. Hence, consideration is given to the incorporation of multidimensional aspects of learning and experience in Holocaust education in order to enhance students' understanding on cognitive, emotional and moral levels. This book will help Holocaust educators and curriculum developers to design Holocaust education programs and attune them to the nature and the needs of the current generation. It is intended to prepare educators to initiate and lead programs and encounters designed to teach today's youth about the Holocaust from multiple perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1935-1945)xStudy and teaching. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aBrutin, Batya.1 aCassuto, David.1 aDavidovitch, Nitza, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aDorot, Ruth.1 aGawron, Edyta.1 aGerstenfeld, Manfred.1 aGil, Zvi.1 aHaber, Lily.1 aKaźmierczak, Marek.1 aKnobler, Haim Y.1 aOrgad, Zvi.1 aSoen, Dan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aUr-Leurer, Osnat.1 aZemishlany, Zvi.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertASP eBook Package Backlist 2008-2015z978311068814640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618113115423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781618113115.jpg  a978-3-11-068814-6  ASP eBook Package Backlist 2008-2015c2008d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HU